        "import time\n",
        "\n",
        "# Ensure trips view is tied to df\n",
        "df.createOrReplaceTempView(\"trips\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 1: Demonstrate caching\n",
        "# Run a query before caching\n",
        "start = time.time()\n",
        "spark.sql(\"SELECT AVG(fare_amount) AS avg_fare FROM trips\").show()\n",
        "time_before_cache = time.time() - start\n",
        "print(\"Query time before caching:\", time_before_cache, \"seconds\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Cache the cleaned DataFrame\n",
        "df.cache()\n",
        "df.count # force cache to happen\n",
        "\n",
        "# Run the same query after caching\n",
        "start = time.time()\n",
        "spark.sql(\"SELECT AVG(fare_amount) AS avg_fare FROM trips\").show()\n",
        "time_after_cache = time.time() - start\n",
        "print(\"Query time after caching:\", time_after_cache, \"seconds\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 2: Write cleaned data to Parquet partitioned by pickup_hour\n",
        "# Partitioning allows Spark to skip irrelevant data when filtering by pickup_hour\n",
        "df.write.mode(\"overwrite\").partitionBy(\"pickup_hour\").parquet(\"cleaned_trips_partitioned\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 3: Read back a single partition (e.g., hour 17) and verify partition pruning\n",
        "# Only data for pickup_hour = 17 should be scanned\n",
        "df_partitioned = spark.read.parquet(\"cleaned_trips_partitioned\")\n",
        "df_partitioned.filter(\"pickup_hour = 17\").show(5)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 4: Use explain() on one of the SQL queries\n",
        "# This shows the physical execution plan\n",
        "query_plan = spark.sql(\"\"\"\n",
        "SELECT pickup_hour, COUNT(*) AS trip_count\n",
        "FROM trips\n",
        "GROUP BY pickup_hour\n",
        "ORDER BY trip_count DESC\n",
        "LIMIT 5\n",
        "\"\"\")\n",
        "query_plan.explain()\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The physical plan shows how Spark executes the query step by step first beginning with a FileScan of the Parquet dataset to read the raw taxi trip records, then applies a Filter to remove rows with nulls or invalid values such as negative fares or drop‑offs before pickups. After filtering, Spark performs a Project stage to compute new derived columns like trip duration, speed, tip percentage, and pickup hour/day. Once the data is prepared, Spark uses a HashAggregate to group records by pickup hour and count the number of trips, but because grouping requires data to be redistributed across partitions, an Exchange operation is triggered to shuffle the data using hash partitioning. Finally, Spark applies a TakeOrderedAndProject to sort the results by trip count and limit the output to the top five busiest hours. In short, the plan illustrates the typical Spark pipeline of scanning, filtering, projecting, shuffling, aggregating, and ordering to produce the desired summary."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "k06iy7EpVNuX"
      }
    },
